## How to fix common errors

### Prisma authentication error
If you see P1000 authentication failed:
- Go to Supabase project settings.
- Reset the database password if needed.
- Update the password inside backend/.env DATABASE_URL.
- Run npx prisma db pull again.

### Java not found
If Java is not recognized:
- Install Java 17 Temurin.
- Set JAVA_HOME.
- Restart the terminal.
- Run java -version to confirm.

### Android device offline
If adb says device offline:
- Unplug the phone.
- Replug it.
- Allow USB debugging on the phone.
- Run adb kill-server and then adb devices.

### Expo Go does not work
LiveKit uses native WebRTC modules, so Expo Go will not work.
You must build and install a dev client with:
```bash
npx expo prebuild
npx expo run:android
```

### Android SDK not found
If the build says Android SDK location not found:
- Set ANDROID_HOME to the SDK path.
- Confirm the SDK exists in your Windows user AppData folder.

### colors.xml error
If iconBackground is missing:
- Open frontend/android/app/src/main/res/values/colors.xml
- Add:
```xml
<color name="iconBackground">#FFFFFF</color>
```

### Path length error
If Windows path length is too long:
- Move the project to a shorter folder path like C:\dev\safick.
- Reinstall node_modules there.
- Clear stale build caches.

### Stale .cxx / Gradle cache
If the build keeps referencing the old project path:
- Stop the Gradle daemon.
- Delete stale .cxx folders.
- Delete old react-native-reanimated and react-native-worklets build caches.
- Run the Android build again.

## What to do if the build still fails

1. Stop Gradle.
2. Delete stale caches.
3. Verify Java 17 is set.
4. Verify Android SDK path is set.
5. Make sure the project is in a short path.
6. Reinstall node_modules.
7. Run npx expo run:android again.

## Final note
The goal was to keep the app structure unchanged and only connect LiveKit to the existing live screens. Most problems came from Windows Android build setup, not the LiveKit code itself.